cs.IT, cs.NI, cs.SY, cs.MM, cs.CE

Reasoning: 
1. cs.IT (Information Theory): The paper proposes a new SWIPT system aided by intelligent reflecting surfaces (IRS) to enhance the efficiency of wireless power transfer. The paper discusses the optimization of transmit precoders and reflect phase shifts to maximize the weighted sum-power received by energy harvesting receivers (EHRs) subject to individual signal-to-interference-plus-noise ratio (SINR) constraints for information decoding receivers (IDRs). This falls under the domain of information theory.
2. cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture): The paper discusses the deployment of an IRS to assist a multi-antenna access point (AP) to serve multiple IDRs and EHRs. This involves the design of a network architecture that can support the proposed SWIPT system.
3. cs.SY (Systems and Control): The paper proposes efficient algorithms to obtain suboptimal solutions for the non-convex optimization problem of maximizing the weighted sum-power received by EHRs. This involves the design of control systems to optimize the performance of the SWIPT system.
4. cs.MM (Multimedia): The paper discusses the use of massive low-cost passive elements that are able to reflect signals with adjustable phase shifts to achieve a high passive beamforming gain. This technology can be used to enhance the performance of multimedia applications that require high data rates and efficient power transfer.
